    "name_suffix": "_bash",
    "teacher_markdown": "### **🧾 What to Prepare:**\r\n\r\n* #### Print copies of the <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1YDGmbxZSHZhvMWVPzoawNm0ceKRoPffgt1kc0HQDWhk/view\" target=\"blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Client Stories Activity Guide</a> for each student.\r\n* #### Preview the <a href=\"https://studio.code.org/courses/programming-with-music-lab-2025/units/1/lessons/1/levels/1\" target=\"blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">song prototypes</a> in Code Studio so you're familiar with what students will hear.\r\n* #### Make a copy of the <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/14X814gR4KUxcZKEkbqhOSR03pg-8XKWZZMhIn7AJo4w/template/preview\" target=\"blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">lesson plan slides</a> and adjust for your teaching context as necessary. \r\n* #### Have a plan for how you’ll group students in pairs - this activity is most effective with discussion.\r\n* #### Print or copy our <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/12R4e0xxMFBbkyu4gaXbXfwyLba-OjivpRNggZlw8hiE/edit?usp=sharing\" target=\"blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Musical Terms Anchor Charts</a> onto chart paper to provide students with a shared vocabulary and support meaningful collaboration.\r\n\r\n### **💡 Tips for Teaching:**\r\n* #### Focus on student reasoning, not just answers. There may be multiple \"right\" matches between clients and songs. Encourage students to explain their thinking and listen to others' perspectives.\r\n* #### Model how to explore the Example Player. This is the first time students will interact with Music Lab’s embedded players, so take a moment to show how it works and where to listen for differences.\r\n* #### Encourage creative exploration. Especially during the sound library portion, let students experiment and have fun. \r\n* #### Use the reflection to reinforce empathy. Ask students how their song design choices might change if they had to create music for a different client. This builds empathy and expands their creative lens.",
